#: ../../../getting_started/using_jupyter.md:2
msgid "Using Jupyter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started/using_jupyter.md:4
msgid ""
"When it comes to rendering with VTK in Jupyter, there are several options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started/using_jupyter.md:6
msgid ""
"To harness the full power of VTK in Jupyter, you may want to leverage "
"[PyVista](https://docs.pyvista.org/) and [Trame](https://kitware.github.io/"
"trame/index.html). PyVista exposes a high-level interface to VTK for "
"plotting and when combined with Trame, empowers users to bring the full "
"power of VTK to a Jupyter notebook. We have [a post on the VTK discourse "
"about this](https://discourse.vtk.org/t/pyvista-trame-jupyter-3d-"
"visualization/10610). See PyVista's documentation for more information on "
"using PyVista's wrappings of VTK in Jupyter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started/using_jupyter.md:14
msgid ""
"[itkwidgets](https://itkwidgets.readthedocs.io/en/latest) is one example of "
"a domain-specific Jupyter viewer built on VTK. To try out itkwidgets, check "
"[this example](https://colab.research.google.com/github/"
"InsightSoftwareConsortium/itkwidgets/blob/main/examples/integrations/vtk/"
"vtkImageData.ipynb)."
msgstr ""

